</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/bb1d9c560d4f528c9c4ebd99e0e3d15561854d91" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -0.838ex; width:18.878ex; height:3.176ex;" alt="{\displaystyle O((\log a+\log b)^{2}).}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>The square in this complexity comes from the fact that division by <span class="texhtml">2</span> and subtraction take a time that is proportional to the number of <a href="/wiki/Bit" title="Bit">bits</a> of the input.
</p><p>The computational complexity is usually given in terms of the length <span class="texhtml"><i>n</i></span> of the input. Here, this length is <span class="texhtml"><i>n</i> = log <i>a</i> + log <i>b</i></span>, and the complexity is thus
</p>
<dl><dd><span class="mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"  alttext="{\displaystyle O(n^{2})}">
